body:
From #2064

@stweil commented on Nov 19, 2018

>On Windows @noahmetzger recently reported that not using SSE or AVX is faster than using AVX.

@amitdo commented on Sep 5

>Is there a separate issue for this?

@stweil commented on Sep 5

>I am not sure whether this is still true and will ask @noahmetzger on Monday or test it myself.

I believe that the recent improvements in the build system brought a major regression: `make install` does not (build and) install libtesseract.so anymore.

This is a huge problem for other software that wants to link to Tesseract (like `tesserocr`). Their build will fall back to the static library, but this can fail by not pulling in Tesseract's dependencies (like `-llept`), or by missing things like `-fsanitize=address`.

@stweil do you want me to give detailed error messages?

I'm using Tesseract 3.05.02 (packaged in Fedora 29), and I'm using it to read text in a code editor (same monospace font, different colors and styles -monospace/italic-)

The command I'm using is `tesseract -c preserve_interword_spaces=1 -psm6 <input> <output>`. I need plain text, not HTML.
I didn't find a way to preserve the line indentation, even a relative one.
So if I read a text editor that contains
```
a {
    color: red;
}
```
Tesseract tells me it
```
a {
color: red;
}
```
and ignores to whitespaces before the line.

It would be a good addition to have an option like `preserve_prefix_whitespaces=1` to get the prefix indentation part of the text.
